# 1830. Minimum Number of Operations to Make String Sorted
## O(n × 26) — Permutation Rank via Combinatorics

---

## Problem Statement

- Each operation = "previous permutation" (find rightmost descent, swap, reverse suffix).
- Return how many operations until sorted = **lexicographic rank** of `s` mod 10⁹+7.

---

## Core Idea — Permutation Rank Formula

**Key insight**: each operation transforms `s` into the lexicographically previous permutation. So the answer = number of permutations that come before `s` = its 0-indexed rank.

**Formula**: for each position `i`, count permutations of `s[i..n-1]` that start with a character **strictly less than** `s[i]` (while `s[0..i-1]` is already fixed):

```
contribution_i = (# chars in s[i..n-1] that are < s[i]) × (n-i-1)! / ∏ freq[j]!
```

Where `freq` = frequency of each character in `s[i..n-1]` **including** `s[i]` itself.

**Critical**: compute `smaller` and `perms` using `freq` **before removing** `s[i]`, then remove `s[i]` afterwards.

**Why?**  
Permutations of `s[i..n-1]` starting with char `c < s[i]`:
```
= ∑_{c < s[i]} freq[c] × (n-i-2)! / (freq[c]-1)! / ∏_{j≠c} freq[j]!
= (n-i-1)! × ∑_{c<s[i]} freq[c] / ∏_j freq[j]!
= smaller × (n-i-1)! / ∏_j freq[j]!
```

where `freq` is the **full** remaining frequency (before removing `s[i]`).

---

## Full Optimal Implementation (C#)

```csharp
public class Solution {
    const int MOD = 1_000_000_007;

    public int MakeStringSorted(string s) {
        int n = s.Length;

        long[] fact = new long[n+1], invFact = new long[n+1];
        fact[0] = 1;
        for (int i = 1; i <= n; i++) fact[i] = fact[i-1] * i % MOD;
        invFact[n] = ModPow(fact[n], MOD-2, MOD);
        for (int i = n-1; i >= 0; i--) invFact[i] = invFact[i+1] * (i+1) % MOD;

        int[] freq = new int[26];
        foreach (char c in s) freq[c-'a']++;

        long res = 0;
        for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
            int ci = s[i] - 'a';

            // Count chars in s[i..n-1] that are < s[i] (using freq BEFORE removing s[i])
            int smaller = 0;
            for (int j = 0; j < ci; j++) smaller += freq[j];

            // Perms of s[i..n-1] starting with char < s[i]
            // = smaller × (n-i-1)! / ∏ freq[j]!
            long perms = fact[n-i-1];
            foreach (int f in freq) perms = perms * invFact[f] % MOD;

            res = (res + smaller * perms) % MOD;

            freq[ci]--; // NOW remove s[i] from freq
        }

        return (int)res;
    }

    long ModPow(long b, long e, long mod) {
        long r = 1; b %= mod;
        for (; e > 0; e >>= 1) { if ((e&1)==1) r=r*b%mod; b=b*b%mod; }
        return r;
    }
}
```

